<br>
Would a similar event be necessary to focus the world on an intense effort to get off the planet? What circumstances could provide us with a burning intensity to get off of the Earth? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=spacedrive@nuclearspace>Spacedrive</A> at: 3/7/03 9:15:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 175<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/8/03 4:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=32.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/bioh.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What if we were forced to go into space?</span><hr size=1> We have had at least one major strike since the beginning of our industrial age. <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www-th.bo.infn.it/tunguska/" target="top">Tunguska in 1908.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> I have heard that there may have been some lesser, but still serious strikes in remote areas – but I cannot find any reference to them at this time. <br>
<br>
Sadly, I think that we might be doomed. Politicians only think to the next election, most businessmen only to the next quarter. Since we couldn’t save everybody with an exodus, there would be a huge protest against racists rich elitists who think they know better than god/fate/luck. Also, a lot of people would just deny (oh, it wont hit the earth. What do those eggheads know – 100 years is a long time) as well as those who think some major breakthrough is just around the corner (in 30 years we will have unlimited gerbil-powered spacecraft capable of FTL speeds while being environmentally friendly, so why waste the effort on nasty atomic rockets).<br>
<br>
We can do remarkable things, and given the threat we might make it. I don’t think we would go for the stars though. It would be much easier to establish space colonies, orbital habitats, even Martian and lunar colonies. From such high ground we could watch the disaster (we do, as a species, tend to love a good disaster – as long as it happens to someone else). Then, when things have calmed down we could reclaim the Earth.<br>
<br>
Personally, I think star travel will prove extremely difficult. Our most likely means of stellar colonization will be with von Newman machines carrying genetic materials and huge databases to educate the new humans on distant worlds.<br>
<br>
Back to your question – what could motivate humanity to bail on the earth? Well, impending major impact might, a devastating biological disaster, tectonic upheavals on a massive scale, and of course the ever present threat of another Brady Bunch variety hour reunion special.  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
